	     Johannesburg – The National Prosecuting Authority has given President Jacob Zuma until November 30 to make representations over his corruption charges. NPA spokesperson Luvuyo Mfaku, in a statement, said: "As a result, Mr Zuma has been advised through his lawyers that he has until 30 November 2017 to submit any envisaged representations to the NDPP." The NPA said the National Director of Public Prosecutions "is of the view that in light of the judgment of the SCA, it appears that any further representations envisaged by Mr Zuma should relate to issues not previously considered". The Supreme Court of Appeal ruled earlier this month that the NPA's 2009 decision to drop the charges against Zuma was irrational. More to follow. Read the full statement here:   24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  